{"title":"LoGoNet: Towards Accurate 3D Object Detection with Local-to-Global Cross-Modal Fusion","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Global LiDAR–camera fusion often lacks precise cross-modal alignment and fuses over the whole scene, diluting object-relevant cues.","method":"LoGoNet introduces a Global Fusion module with Centroid Dynamic Fusion (CDF) that represents each non-empty voxel by its point centroid rather than the voxel center to better match the true 3D surface geometry. These centroids are projected to the image plane and used as reference points for deformable cross-attention with learned offsets to aggregate nearby image features. The voxel features (queries) are fused with sampled image features (keys/values), concatenated and compressed via FFN, and ROI pooling over fused voxels produces proposal features for refinement."},{"problem":"Purely global fusion misses fine-grained, proposal-level geometry and context needed to detect small, distant, or occluded objects.","method":"LoGoNet proposes a Local Fusion (LoF) module that divides each proposal into uniform 3D grids and encodes raw point cloud position information per grid via a Position Information Encoder (PIE), including relative grid location and local point statistics. Grid centers are projected to the image plane to sample local image features with learned offsets, and cross-attention fuses these samples with the encoded grid features. The result is a locally fused ROI-grid feature that captures fine-grained region-level multi-modal cues."},{"problem":"Features fused at global and local levels are computed independently and lack interaction, limiting their combined effectiveness.","method":"LoGoNet adds a Feature Dynamic Aggregation (FDA) module that applies self-attention over the ROI-grid features to build relationships among grid points and enable interaction between globally and locally fused representations. A transformer encoder layer with residual connections aggregates these features into a more informative multi-modal representation, which is then used for second-stage bounding box refinement."}]}
